### shader-execution-and-clip-type-refs (complete)

Map the current dual-path shader execution and identify the cutover point where M4 makes native graph operations the write path, audit clipType storage and projection, and identify repair/resolution states.

- DUAL-PATH SHADER EXECUTION: Legacy mutations flow through `clip.update`/`app.update` timeline patch ops → `extractGraphPreviewOps()` (timeline-patch.ts:1889) → `GraphShaderAssignOp`/`GraphShaderRemoveOp` → `applyGraphPreviewOperations()`. The native functions `assignTimelineClipShader`/`assignTimelinePostprocessShader` (timeline-domain.ts:377,402) write into `clip.app.shader` / `config.app.shaderPostprocess` but are only invoked from the timeline-patch compile path and tests. No UI or command module calls them directly — all shader writes currently enter through legacy patch operations.
- NATIVE PREVIEW PATH EXISTS BUT IS NOT THE WRITE PATH: `GraphShaderAssignOp`/`GraphShaderRemoveOp` (patchPreview.ts:43,53) and their applicators `applyShaderAssign`/`applyShaderRemove` (patchPreview.ts:171,205) operate on the shader array in the snapshot (`TimelineShaderSummary[]`), NOT on `clip.app`. This native path is used exclusively for preview/diagnostics via `applyGraphPreviewOperations()` (patchPreview.ts:774). The public SDK timeline patch families do NOT include `shader.assign`/`shader.remove` — they are reserved. M4 must promote them to public write-path operations.
- CUTOVER PLAN: The `extractGraphPreviewOps()` bridge (timeline-patch.ts:1878-1970) currently scans legacy `clip.update`/`app.update` ops and extracts shader payloads into native graph ops. Post-M4, new shader writes must use native `shader.assign`/`shader.remove` as public timeline patch families, bypassing the bridge. Legacy payloads in `clip.update`/`app.update` become compatibility reads only. The bridge function can remain for backward-compatible preview but must not be the write path for new operations.
- CLIPTYPE STORAGE: `clipType` is stored as a flat string property on clip nodes in `graphProjector.ts:303` (`clipType: clip.clipType`). It is declared as `ClipType` (union) in types/index.ts:346 but widened to string at schema level (line 68). There is NO `clipType`-to-`ContributionRef` projection in the graph today — `clipType` does not appear as a contribution node or edge.
- CLIPTYPE AND CONTRIBUTION INDEX: `clipType` is listed as a 'reserved future kind' in `extensionSurface.ts:706` alongside effect, transition, parser, agentTool, agent. The `normalizeExtensionRuntime` doc (line 705) explicitly separates 'bridged M1 contributions (slot, dialog, panel, inspectorSection) from reserved future kinds (effect, transition, clipType, parser, agentTool, agent)'. Clip types currently enter the contribution index with `status: 'inactive-reserved'`, which the reference resolver maps to `ReferenceState: 'inactive-reserved'` and `COMPOSITION_DIAGNOSTIC_CODE.INACTIVE_RESERVED_REF`.
- CLIPTYPE-TO-CONTRIBUTION-REF PROJECTION DESIGN: To project clipType as a ContributionRef, M4 needs to: (a) add a `consumes` edge from each clip node to a `contribution:clipType:<extensionId>:<contributionId>` node (matching the pattern used for shaders in graphProjector.ts:453-500), (b) use the ClipTypeRegistryRecord's `ownerExtensionId` and `contributionId` to build the ContributionRef, (c) the ContributionRef kind would be `'clipType'`. The `resolveCompositionReferences` call already handles arbitrary ref kinds through `contributionRefKey(ref)`.
- DIAGNOSTIC CODES ARE COMPLETE: All needed reference-state codes exist in diagnostics.ts: `MISSING_REF`, `DISABLED_REF`, `INACTIVE_RESERVED_REF`, `INVALID_PACKAGE_REF`, `DUPLICATE_REF`, `SETTINGS_ERROR_REF`, `RUNTIME_ERROR_REF`, `VERSION_INCOMPATIBLE_REF`, `UNKNOWN_REF`. The `referenceStateDiagnosticCode()` function maps all 10 ReferenceState values to their codes. Additional composition codes (`DUPLICATE_SCOPE`, `SCOPE_OCCUPIED`) cover shader scope conflicts. No new diagnostic codes are needed for M4.
- DUPLICATE SCOPE REJECTION: Already implemented in `validateShaderComposition` (shaderValidation.ts) and `buildDuplicateScopeDiagnostics` (graphProjector.ts:252-288). The `applyShaderAssign` in patchPreview.ts:171 already removes any existing shader for the same scope before adding (single-occupancy enforcement). The graph projector's `buildDuplicateScopeDiagnostics` catches existing duplicates from stored data.
- REPAIR PLACEHOLDER CONTRACT: The `CompositionDiagnosticDetail` interface (diagnostics.ts:144-195) already carries `nextAction?: Record<string, unknown>` for planner repair actions. The `COMPOSITION_DIAGNOSTIC_CODE.MISSING_REF` and `DISABLED_REF` are already defined with warning severity. Repair actions would be attached via the `nextAction` field. The `referenceStateSeverity()` function (diagnostics.ts:294) classifies `missing` and `inactive-reserved` as warnings and all other non-resolved states as errors.
- NO EXISTING CANARY: A search for `clip-local-shader-canary` or `canary` across the entire repository returned zero results. The canary must be newly created in `examples/video-editor-extension/` as part of M4.
- RENDER-PATH INTEGRATION: The `TimelineRenderer.tsx` already reads shaders via `getTimelinePostprocessShader` (line 1231) and the shader registry snapshot. Clip-level shaders are read via `getTimelineClipShader` from `clip.app.shader`. M4's graph-owned shader assignment must feed into this existing render read path so that shader-uniform keyframes can be resolved by the same `resolveAnimatedParams` pipeline that handles automation keyframes (imported at line 45).

